Reasoning: The paper deals with topics related to information theory, computational complexity, logic, cryptography, and data structures. Specifically, it introduces new concepts such as zeta numbers, natural halting probabilities, and natural complexity of Turing machines, and relates them to existing concepts such as Chaitin's Omega number, halting probability, and program-size complexity. It also proposes a classification of Turing machines based on their zeta numbers and proves various results on randomness and partial randomness. These topics are relevant to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.IT (Information Theory), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science), cs.CR (Cryptography and Security), and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
